"German: habitational name from a place of that name in Westphalia."]},{"name":"Heryford","meanings":["Altered form of English   Hereford  ."]},{"name":"Heriford","meanings":["Altered form of English   Hereford  ."]},{"name":"Harford","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Gloucestershire): variant of   Hereford  ."]},{"name":"Havard","meanings":["English and Welsh (Brecknockshire and Glamorgan): habitational name from Haverfordwest (Pembrokeshire), from Old English <i>hæfer</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","English and Welsh (Brecknockshire and Glamorgan): in some cases, the name may also be a variant of   Hereford  .","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Hahward</i>, composed of the elements <i>hah</i>, which is unexplained, and <i>ward</i> ‘guard’."]},{"name":"Hurford","meanings":["English (Devon and Somerset): variant of   Hereford  ."]}]},{"name":"Mabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a nickname from the Old French vocabulary word <i>amabel</i>, <i>amable</i> ‘lovely’ (akin to modern English <i>amiable</i> ‘friendly, good-humoured’). The initial vowel began to be lost as early as the 12th century (the same woman is referred to as both <i>Mabilia</i> and <i>Amabilia</i> in a document of  1185 ), but a short vowel in the resulting first syllable was standard, giving a rhyme with <i>babble</i>, until the 19th century, when people began to pronounce the name to rhyme with <i>table</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mabel Hereford was born about 1130, in Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Sybil de Neufmarché. She had at least 2 sons with Philip de Astley. She died about 1163, at the age of 35."},"et":{"about 1130–about 1163 or 1164":"umbes 1130–umbes 1163","1130–1163":"1130–1163","1136–1220":"1136–1220","1122–1165":"1122–1165","1153–1220":"1153–1220","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1100–1143":"1100–1143","Aft 1143":"pä